}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":16,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"William Holbroke was born about 1274, in Suffolk, England. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs Holbroke. He died after 1301."},"et":{"about 1274–after 1301":"umbes 1274–pärast 1301","–Female":"Surnud","1302–1318":"1302–1318","1274–1301":"1274–1301","1302":"1302","1301":"1301","1274":"1274","1318":"1318","about 1274":"umbes 1274","after 1301":"pärast 1301","1290":"1290","Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England":"Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1274–after 1301":"noin 1274–1301 jälkeen","–Female":"Kuollut","1302–1318":"1302–1318","1274–1301":"1274–1301","1302":"1302","1301":"1301","1274":"1274","1318":"1318","about 1274":"noin 1274","after 1301":"1301 jälkeen","1290":"1290","Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England":"Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"about 1274–after 1301":"environ 1274–après 1301","–Female":"Décédée","1302–1318":"1302–1318","1274–1301":"1274–1301","